04717nam a22005535i 9780822387961DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223879617 a10.1515/97808223879612doi  a(DE-B1597)554363  a(OCoLC)1224279479  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1190b.S3498 2006 7aSOC0100002bisacsh04a305.42012221 aShohat, Ella, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaboo Memories, Diasporic Voices /cElla Shohat; Caren Kaplan, Robyn Wiegman. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b60 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tGendered Cartographies of Knowledge: Area Studies, Ethnic Studies, and Postcolonial Studies -- tGender and the Culture of Empire: Toward a Feminist Ethnography of the Cinema -- tSacred Word, Profane Image: Theologies of Adaptation -- tThe Cinema after Babel: Language, Difference, Power (with Robert Stam) -- t''Lasers for Ladies'': Endo Discourse and the Inscriptions of Science -- tDisorienting Cleopatra: A Modern Trope of Identity -- tTaboo Memories, Diasporic Visions: Columbus, Palestine, and Arab-Jews -- tNotes on the ''Post-Colonial'' -- tPost-Fanon and the Colonial: A Situational Diagnosis -- tPost-Third Worldist Culture: Gender, Nation, and the Cinema -- tRupture and Return: Zionist Discourse and the Study of Arab-Jews -- tThe ''Postcolonial'' in Translation: Reading Edward Said between English and Hebrew -- tIndex -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS AND CREDITS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTaboo Memories, Diasporic Voices brings together for the first time a selection of trailblazing essays by Ella Shohat, an internationally renowned theorist of postcolonial and cultural studies of Iraqi-Jewish background. Written over the past two decades, these twelve essays-some classic, some less known, some new-trace a powerful intellectual trajectory as Shohat rigorously teases out the consequences of a deep critique of Eurocentric epistemology, whether to rethink feminism through race, nationalism through ethnicity, or colonialism through sexuality.Shohat's critical method boldly transcends disciplinary and geographical boundaries. She explores such issues as the relations between ethnic studies and area studies, the paradoxical repercussions for audio-visual media of the "graven images" taboo, the allegorization of race through the refiguring of Cleopatra, the allure of imperial popular culture, and the gender politics of medical technologies. She also examines the resistant poetics of exile and displacement; the staging of historical memory through the commemorations of the two 1492s, the anomalies of the "national" in Zionist discourse, the implications of the hyphen in the concept "Arab-Jew," and the translation of the debates on orientalism and postcolonialism across geographies. Taboo Memories, Diasporic Voices not only illuminates many of the concerns that have animated the study of cultural politics over the past two decades; it also points toward new scholarly possibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387961zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter